<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911108-0090</DOCNO><DOCID>911108-0090.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Cablevision Systems Corp.:   Firm Posts Narrower Loss   On Revenue Jump of 8%</HL><DATE>11/08/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CVC</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Cablevision Systems Corp., Woodbury, N.Y., reportednarrower losses on increased revenue and cash flow for thethird quarter.   Cablevision posted a net loss of $50.7 million, or $2.32 ashare, compared with $74.5 million, or $3.38 a share, a yearearlier. The recent period included a gain of $5.8 millionfrom the sale of assets. Revenue jumped 8% to $152.7 millionfrom $141.4 million a year ago, helped by rate increases andsubscriber growth.</LP><TEXT>   Operating cash flow before depreciation and amortizationrose 11% to $66.5 million in the quarter. For the ninemonths, the net loss was $158.6 million, or $7.23 a share,compared with $216.3 million, or $9.85 a share, last year.The latest nine-month figure includes a gain of $21.7 millionfrom the sale of assets. Revenue was up to $450 million from$416.4 million.   Cablevision is the nation's eighth-largest operator oflocal cable systems, reaching 1.4 million homes.</TEXT></DOC>